Linda Mary Montano Papers

Contents

Series I: Art Practice

Scope and Content

This series documents Montano's work as a performance artist and writer.

Subseries A: Art Administration

Scope and Content

Subseries A includes Montano's administrative papers, which include informal and formal proposals for performances, videos, and text. More informal proposals take the form of handwritten performance ideas, many of which were realized and exist in other parts of her archive. This series also contains her grant applications, loan agreements, business correspondence, and emails with arts organizations, museums, and foundations that range from the beginning of her career to 2014.

Arrangement

Subseries A is arranged alphabetically by folder title.

Subseries B: Writing

Scope and Content

Subseries B follows Montano's work as the author of several published works. These works include Art in Everyday Life, Letters from Linda Montano, and You Too Are a Performance Artist. The subseries also includes drafts and interviews Montano compiled for the book Performance Artists Talking in the '80s, in which artists talk about food, sex, death, and money. There are also book galleys, correspondence, artists' statements, and smaller pieces written for articles and exhibition catalogues.

Arrangement

This subseries is arranged alphabetically by title of work.

Subseries C: Interviews

Scope and Content

Subseries C includes interviews Montano conducted for her book project entitled Performance Artists Talking in the '80s. It also contains material related to interviews of Montano by others for articles, both published and unpublished.

Subseries D: Research

Scope and Content

Subseries D contains mostly handwritten research and articles on a variety of subjects that informed Montano's art/life practices. Her research also serves as an extension of her art documentation. Themes include spirituality, astrology, health, religion, grief, meditation, and music.

Subseries E: Press

Scope and Content

This subseries tracks press about Montano's career from the 1970s to the early 2000s. It includes promotional postcards, advertisements, and press releases. It also contains newspaper clippings, reviews and articles written about her art and performances, from publications like High Performance Magazine to the New York Times.

Subseries G: Artworks

Scope and Content

This series contains some of Montano's artwork, including her series of "Dad Paintings," and her "Shoe" series. It also documents the art she produced and outifits she during her performance "7 Years of Living Art," and her study of the chakras. Other pieces include prints, pencil sketches, paintings, drawings. Montano also kept annotated photo albums and scrapbooks that were created both by her and her grandmother. A large portion of artwork can also be found in Oversize Series I, Subseries G.

Series II: Inspirational People and Collaborators

Scope and Content

This series consists of materials related to important collaborations Montano has fostered throughout her career and lifetime. Key collaborators include Annie Sprinkle, Dr. Mehta, Dr. Mishru, Mitchell Payne, Pauline Oliveros, and Tehching Hsieh. Material in this series reflects Montano's performance art/life process, blending the personal with the professional. It includes correspondence, photographic material, research, notes, collaborative works, and press and promotional material.

Series III: Correspondence

Scope and Content

This series contains primarily Montano's personal correspondence, and is arranged alphabetically by last name, when indicated. It includes Montano's collection of fan and student correspondence. Business correspondence can be found in Series I, Subseries A. Correspondence from collaborators and family can be found in Series II and V.

31142054887958box: 45, folder: 9 (Material Type: Mixed Materials)

Series IV: Teaching

Scope and Content

This series contains syllabi, academic papers, correspondence, and quarterly student evaluations from Montano's time as a professor and guest lecturer at several different institutions, including the University of Texas at Austin, UCLA, and San Francisco Art Institute. A bulk of the material also contains Montano's student files, which contain resumes and a collection of theses that discuss, interpret and analyze Montano's work. Also represented in this series is the in-depth documentation of Montano's request for tenure at UT Austin. This material, which includes writing, correspondence, statements, and press, formed the narrative for Montano's performance piece "Tenure."

Abrams, Damali, 2007

Series V: Family and Juvenilia

Scope and Content

This series consists of documents, photographic materials, and artworks that relate to Montano's childhood, adolescence, and family. It includes diaries, certificates, scrapbooks, and materials related to family members and Montano's time spent at a convent between 1960 and 1962.

Series VI: Commercially Released Media

Arrangement

All commercially released media is arranged into 3 subseries: audio, video, and vinyl. Within subseries, media is arranged chronologically by year of release. All undated material can be found at the end of each subseries.

Conditions Governing Access

Commercially released media copies are available by appointment for reading room viewing and listening only. Please contact fales.library@nyu.edu, 212-998-2596.

Subseries A: Sound recordings

Arrangement

Subseries A is arranged chronologically, where dates were designated.

This series is divided into three subseries: audio, video, and film. Within subseries, media is arranged alphabetically by title.

Audiovisual materials in this series have not been preserved and may not be available to researchers.

Linda Mary Montano Archived Website, February 2016- May 2017

box: Electronic records, E-records: https://wayback.archive-it.org/7078/*/http://www.lindamontano.com/ (Material Type: electronic records)

Extent

2 websites in 2 archived websites.

Creator

Montano, Linda, 1942-

Appraisal

Robots.txt (a piece of code that prevents crawlers from advancing through a site) were ignored during capture with the permission of the site owner.

There were six videos included on Linda Montano's website that were not present on the hard drive associated with this collection. These were crawled separately to ensure adequate capture.

Linda Montano's blog (http://lindamarymontano.blogspot.com) was also crawled separately to ensure adequate capture.

Crawl was limited to domains and subdomains of http://www.lindamontano.com and http://lindamarymontano.blogspot.com in order to remain within the collection scope and data constraints.
